        &#95;base value;                                                           \\
        using <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/safepointirverifier-cpp/#ae96315ee246bd4a509133af84c88c5e1">BaseType</a> = &#95;base;                                                \\
    &#125;;</>}>
YAML I/O does conversion based on types. But often native data types are just a typedef of built in intergral types (e.g. int). But the C++ type matching system sees through the typedef and all the typedefed types look like a built in type. This will cause the generic YAML I/O conversion to be used. To provide better control over the YAML conversion, you can use this macro instead of typedef. It will create a class with one field and automatic conversion operators to and from the base type. Based on BOOST&#95;STRONG&#95;TYPEDEF. <a href="#ab74df4ad631bb362ad7d41fd875f0481">More...</a>

        &#95;base value;                                                           \\
        using <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/safepointirverifier-cpp/#ae96315ee246bd4a509133af84c88c5e1">BaseType</a> = &#95;base;                                                \\
    &#125;;</>}>
YAML I/O does conversion based on types. But often native data types are just a typedef of built in intergral types (e.g. int). But the C++ type matching system sees through the typedef and all the typedefed types look like a built in type. This will cause the generic YAML I/O conversion to be used. To provide better control over the YAML conversion, you can use this macro instead of typedef. It will create a class with one field and automatic conversion operators to and from the base type. Based on BOOST&#95;STRONG&#95;TYPEDEF.

Definition at line <a href="#l01728">1728</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/support/yamltraits-h">YAMLTraits.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

</SectionDefinition>

<Link id="l00668" /><CodeLine lineNumber="668"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00669" /><CodeLine lineNumber="669"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// 5.1. Character Set</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00670" /><CodeLine lineNumber="670"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// The allowed character range explicitly excludes the C0 control block #x0-#x1F</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00671" /><CodeLine lineNumber="671"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// (except for TAB #x9, LF #xA, and CR #xD which are allowed), DEL #x7F, the C1</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00672" /><CodeLine lineNumber="672"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// control block #x80-#x9F (except for NEL #x85 which is allowed), the surrogate</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00673" /><CodeLine lineNumber="673"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// block #xD800-#xDFFF, #xFFFE, and #xFFFF.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00674" /><CodeLine lineNumber="674"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00675" /><CodeLine lineNumber="675"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Some strings are valid YAML values even unquoted, but without quotes are</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01297" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1297"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// For endian types, we use existing scalar Traits class for the underlying</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01424" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1424"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01425" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1425"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// The Input class is used to parse a yaml document into in-memory structs</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01426" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1426"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// and vectors.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01427" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1427"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01428" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1428"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// It works by using YAMLParser to do a syntax parse of the entire yaml</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01429" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1429"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// document, then the Input class builds a graph of HNodes which wraps</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01430" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1430"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// each yaml Node.  The extra layer is buffering.  The low level yaml</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01431" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1431"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// parser only lets you look at each node once.  The buffering layer lets</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01432" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1432"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// you search and interate multiple times.  This is necessary because</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01433" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1433"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the mapRequired() method calls may not be in the same order</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01434" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1434"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// as the keys in the document.</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01720" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1720"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// YAML I/O does conversion based on types. But often native data types</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01721" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1721"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// are just a typedef of built in intergral types (e.g. int).  But the C++</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01722" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1722"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// type matching system sees through the typedef and all the typedefed types</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01723" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1723"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// look like a built in type. This will cause the generic YAML I/O conversion</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01724" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1724"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// to be used. To provide better control over the YAML conversion, you can</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01725" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1725"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// use this macro instead of typedef.  It will create a class with one field</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01726" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1726"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// and automatic conversion operators to and from the base type.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01727" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1727"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Based on BOOST&#95;STRONG&#95;TYPEDEF</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01728" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1728" lineLink="#ab74df4ad631bb362ad7d41fd875f0481"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;YAML&#95;STRONG&#95;TYPEDEF(&#95;base, &#95;type)                                 \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01729" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1729"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">    struct &#95;type &#123;                                                             \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01730" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1730"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        &#95;type() = default;                                                     \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01731" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1731"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        &#95;type(const &#95;base v) : value(v) &#123;&#125;                                     \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01732" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1732"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        &#95;type(const &#95;type &amp;v) = default;                                       \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01733" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1733"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        &#95;type &amp;operator=(const &#95;type &amp;rhs) = default;                          \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01734" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1734"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        &#95;type &amp;operator=(const &#95;base &amp;rhs) &#123; value = rhs; return &#42;this; &#125;      \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01735" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1735"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        operator const &#95;base &amp; () const &#123; return value; &#125;                      \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01736" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1736"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        bool operator==(const &#95;type &amp;rhs) const &#123; return value == rhs.value; &#125; \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01737" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1737"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        bool operator==(const &#95;base &amp;rhs) const &#123; return value == rhs; &#125;       \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01738" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1738"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        bool operator&lt;(const &#95;type &amp;rhs) const &#123; return value &lt; rhs.value; &#125;   \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01739" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1739"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        &#95;base value;                                                           \\</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01740" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1740"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">        using BaseType = &#95;base;                                                \\</span></CodeLine>
